    Genre: Rock, Pop
    Style: Soft Rock, Ballad
    Year: 1978
    Source: vob-clip.com, 576i, thanks ...

    "Bright Eyes" is a song written by British songwriter Mike Batt and performed by Art Garfunkel. It was written for the soundtrack of the 1978 British animated adventure drama film Watership Down. Rearranged as a pop song from its original form in the film, the track appears on British and European versions of Garfunkel's 1979 Fate for Breakfast and on the US versions of his 1981 album Scissors Cut. "Bright Eyes" topped the UK Singles Chart for six weeks and became Britain's biggest-selling single of 1979, selling over a million copies. Richard Adams, author of the original novel, is reported to have hated the song. A cover of the song was later used explicitly in the Watership Down television series as its theme song.

    The song was written, produced and arranged by Mike Batt for Watership Down, with original director John Hubley requesting a song about death. It plays when the rabbit Hazel, the lead character in the film, almost dies after being wounded by a farmer's gun and Fiver.
    Batt described recording the song as "one of the most difficult sessions" of his career as he wrote the lyrics with his father in mind who was terminally ill with cancer at the time.

    In 2023, the song featured heavily in the fifth episode of season six of the popular Netflix anthology series, Black Mirror , titled "Demon 79", which is set in 1979, the year of the song's release. The song serves as the episode's opening and closing theme.

    Year: 2003
    Source: Master, ProRes 720i

    "I Heard Love Is Blind" is a song recorded and written by English singer-songwriter Amy Winehouse. It was released on October 20, 2003 by Island Records as the fifth track from her debut studio album, Frank. Production for the album took place during 2002 to 2003 and was handled by Winehouse, Salaam Remi, Commissioner Gordon, Jimmy Hogarth and Matt Rowe. Its title alludes to the nature and tone of Winehouse's lyrics on the album, as well as one of her influences, Frank Sinatra.

    This music video is Amy's very first studio performance for camera. She was 20 years old at the time. A few days after having played a double-header at Shepherd's Bush Empire, London, Amy Winehouse returns to the studio for a short, but memorable set at the AOL Sessions on Thursday, May 6th 2004. They recorded five pieces of her debut album 'Frank', as well as a cover version of the 1930s jazz-standard 'There Is No Greater Love'.
